The rocket flies to 3,280ft (1km), remaining stable the entire time, before coming back to land on the ground.

The test follows the successful completion of the Grasshopper program last year, which saw SpaceX gradually increase the ceiling to which its reusable rockets jump.

While for now the technology is only capable of these brief hops, it will eventually be used on fully-fledged launches.

This will enable SpaceX to launch satellites into orbit and then bring most of the rocket that launched them there back to Earth.

This would be a level of reusablility not seen since the Space Shuttle, when Nasa used to recover the two side boosters called Solid Rocket Boosters (SRBs) from the ocean - in addition to the shuttle orbiters themselves being reusable.

But SpaceX’s plan would land the rocket straight back on the pad it took off from and it could be ready for another launch very rapidly.

