He went on to state that it would be 'revolutionary' to ultimately be able to recover a rocket booster and then fly it.

'Now we have been trying to do that for 12 years and haven't yet succeeded, but I feel as though we are finally close to achieving it.'

He added the firm hopes to recover a booster later this year with a view to re-flying it in 2015.

'This would really mark a significant change in the technology of rocketry,' he said.

